MYCOBACTERIUM FORTUITUM, BREAST IMPLANT - BRAZIL: (SAO PAULO)
*************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Thu 4 Dec 2008
Source: PUC Campinas, Correio Popular (Campinas]) report [in Portuguese,
trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
<http://www.puc-campinas.edu.br/servicos/detalhe.asp?id=39487>


The Health Surveillance unit [VISA] in Campinas [in the state of Sao Paulo,
Brazil] issued a technical note to alert health professionals on the
occurrence of post-surgical cases of rapidly growing mycobacterium
infection in the municipality. According to data from the Center for Health
Surveillance [CVS], the total number of confirmed cases reported in the
city so far [as of 4 Dec 2008] to be infected with _Mycobacterium
fortuitum_ is 9 (plus one more case still under investigation), all of whom
had previously undergone cosmetic surgery involving breast implants.
Another 2 cases with similar characteristics have been confirmed in
Indaiatuba [also in the state of Sao Paulo, Brazil]. The coordinator of
health services surveillance in Campinas, Marcia Beltramelli, reported that
the patients had surgery since July [2008]. However, the 1st report [of
this problem] to VISA was in the beginning of November [2008].

This is the 2nd time that Campinas has had an outbreak of mycobacterium
[infection] in women following surgery for silicone implants of the
breasts. The 1st outbreak occurred in 2004, when 14 women were infected.

Marcia [Beltramelli] explained that, following the 1st report, VISA, in
partnership with the CVS and the National Health Surveillance Agency
(ANVISA), initiated an investigation of cases. Brazil reported the 1st
cases of [?all rapidly growing mycobacterium or only _M. fortuitum_]
infection in [the state of] Para in 2001. Since then, the number of cases
has been increasing. During the period 2001 to November of this year
[2008], there were 2122 cases reported, of which 1937 were confirmed, with
about 80 per cent related to laparoscopic surgery.

In Campinas, teams from VISA inspected the institutions involved [those
with post-operative _M. fortuitum_ cases reported] and evaluated the
records of all patients undergoing surgery for breast implants in those
institutions. "The objective [of the investigation] is to obtain data on
confirmed cases and actively search for new cases [that might not have been
reported]," said Marcia [Beltramelli]. Patients and surgeons were contacted
and the cases were followed to verify the evolution [of the infection] and
thereby identify signs, symptoms, and possible common factors. The
investigation also includes an evaluation of the work procedures, cleansing
and sterilization of equipment and material and products used for the
procedures.

"Until now, we have not encountered evidence that points to which stage in
the procedure the contamination occurred," informed Marcia [Beltramelli],
adding that since the outbreak in 2004, VISA had intensified its activities
with the Committees for Hospital Infection Control (CCIHs) in the
municipality, and that in 2009, there will be a special focus on cosmetic
procedures. ANVISA also released a technical report on the outbreak and
established preventive measures. One [of the preventive measures] is a
reporting requirement.

A 27 year old factory worker who agreed to give an interview on condition
of anonymity is one of the victims in Campinas. Two months ago, she had
surgery for silicone breast implants and, afterwards she had the implants
removed, following signs of infection. "I had a lot of pain; the [surgical
site] was red with discharge. It was necessary to open [the surgical site]
and then remove the prostheses," she said. She is being followed by a
plastic surgeon in conjunction with an infectious disease specialist.

--
