[2]
Date: Tue 6 Jan 2009
Source: Abril.com [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
<http://www.abril.com.br/noticias/ciencia-saude/sao-paulo-tem-24-registros-infeccao-micobacterias-228888.shtml>


As of 8 Dec 2008, a total of 24 suspected cases of infection caused by
rapidly growing mycobacteria have been reported in Sao Paulo State, 13 of
which occurred after surgery for prosthetic breast implants, according to
the bulletin released by the State Department of Health before the new year.

The last bulletin of the National Health Surveillance Agency (ANVISA), from
November 2008, pointed out that of a total of 75 reported cases in Brazil,
17 cases were from [the state of] Espirito Santo and 13 [cases were from
the state of] Sao Paulo. The 24 cases [in 2008] exceed the 17 cases
reported in 2005, the last year in which there were reported cases of
[rapidly growing] mycobacterial infections, according the health
department. The report issued yesterday [5 Jan 2009] was in the form of a
bulletin.

Of the total infections reported in [the state of] Sao Paulo, 9 in
Campinas, 7 in Assis, 2 in Indaiatuba, and 1 in Santos have been laboratory
confirmed. In August 2008, the health department had issued an alert about
the disease and released a manual on its prevention. Information came from
the Jornal da Tarde.

