******
[3]
Date: Fri 9 Jan 2009
Source: Cosmo, Brazil Anhanguera News Agency [in Portuguese, trans. & summ.
Mod.JW, edited]
<http://www.cosmo.com.br/noticia/18425/2009-01-09/surto-de-micobacteria-soma-mais-um-caso-em-campinas.html>


Another case of infection with mycobacteria was recorded in Campinas [Sao
Paulo state] this week and 3 other suspected cases are being investigated.
In total, the city has had since March 2008, 11 confirmed cases of
infection in women. The outbreak of infections, which in the rest of the
country mainly affects patients undergoing surgery by laparoscopy, has led
the National Health Surveillance Agency (ANVISA) to propose new measures
for cleaning and sterilization of equipment and materials used in surgery.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[_Mycobacterium fortuitum_ is a non-tuberculous mycobacterium (NTM) (that
is, a grouping outside of the _M. tuberculosis_ complex). _Mycobacterium
fortuitum_ is one of the rapidly growing NTM species (RGM) that produces
mature growth on agar plates within 7 days of incubation. Non-pigmented RGM
are grouped within the _M. fortuitum_ complex and include _M. fortuitum_
and the _M. chelonae/abscessus_ group. The intermediately growing NTM
include _M. marinum_ and _M. gordonae_, are pigmented, and require 7-10
days to produce mature growth on agar plates. Slowly growing NTM include
_M. kansasii_ and _M. avium/intracellulare_ complex and require more than 7
days to produce mature growth on agar plates.

_M. fortuitum_ causes community-acquired skin and soft tissue infection,
usually following trauma in previously healthy individuals and has followed
exposure to contaminated footbaths in nail salons (Sniezek PJ, et al. Arch
Dermatol 2003; 139: 629-34; available at
<http://archderm.ama-assn.org/cgi/content/full/139/5/629>). _M. fortuitum_
is found in natural and processed water, as well as in sewage and dirt,
worldwide. Nosocomial outbreaks of infections due to non-pigmented RGM
species are generally related to use of contaminated water or fluid skin
markers in cosmetic plastic surgery (Safranek TJ, et al. _Mycobacterium
chelonae_ wound infections after plastic surgery employing contaminated
gentian violet skin-marking solution. N Engl J Med 1987; 317: 197-201;
abstract available at
<http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/abstract/317/4/197>), and related to
implanted devices and injection sites.

A prior outbreak of RGM infections following breast implant surgery in
Campinas was reported in 2007 and involved 14 confirmed and 15 suspected
cases who had undergone surgery at 8 different hospitals (Padoveze MC,
Fortaleza CM, Freire MP, et al. Outbreak of surgical infection caused by
non-tuberculous mycobacteria in breast implants in Brazil. J Hosp Infect
2007; 67: 161-7; abstract available at
<http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17881086?dopt=AbstractPlus>). The
isolates obtained from patients at each hospital showed different molecular
patterns, except for isolates from one hospital that repeatedly showed the
same genotype for about one year. No source was apparently identified at
the time.

The current outbreak of _M. fortuitum_ breast implant infections in Brazil
may not be apparently localized to the state of Sao Paulo, but the exact
number of infections due to _M. fortuitum_ versus other non-tuberculous
rapidly growing mycobacteria is unclear from the news releases above. The
results of the epidemiological investigation that should include speciation
and genotyping of the isolates for the current outbreak are eagerly awaited.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Brazil, showing the state of Sao
Paulo, can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?g=3448433&v=-22,-49,5>. - Mod.ML]
